30-Nov-2021. I increased the % for "More than 5.5%" from 80% to 85%. Could put 99% right away but there is still time up to the deadline. According to IHS the US Paper Manufacturing PPI was at 162.6 in Oct this year vs 151.7 in May. The WW price trend for this commodity is much in line with US one due to globalization. And the expectations are that the current paper shortage will last at least up to the mid of 2022. There are other factors contributing to price increase like energy, transportation, inflation. Even if the shortage will phase out in the mid of 2022, the price will not immediately fall back to what is was before. In addition, there could be other factors that would push for a price increase even if the aforementioned ones will cease to affect the price trend. Sustainability is one of them. 28-Jan-2022. Keeping the same percentage as paper shortage continues.
Paper manufacturers are removing capacity from production and re-purposing it to packaging. This will drive up printing paper / writing paper costs.

Working in the publishing industry there is a significant squeeze on paper as with so many industries currently. Labour shortages have been compounded by capacity issues driven from a resurgence in the demand for traditional print. Strongly expect prices to increase heavily as a result.

Sappi, one of the biggest paper producers in Europe, announced in April 2021 a coated and uncoated paper price increase by 7 – 10%. The price change will count for the targeted period May '21 - May '22, as the new Sappi prices will take effect from June 1, 2021. https://www.sappi.com/sappi-europe-announces-price-rise-for-all-coated-uncoated-paper-grades-in-europe-by-7-10

There is widespread drought in forests throughout North America and Europe, along with Brazil. Additionally, forest fires are ravaging these resources which will likely create a shortage for papers. There will also be a competition for wood for building products increasing demand. Hence, it is very likely the price will increase and dramatically so. Drought is projected to affect coffee prices by 25% for 2022, pulp will follow the same route.

much like lumber, PPI for pulp and paper is up 40%; however, much of that demand is for packaging and TP. Writing paper demand is also in the toilet, due to lack of in office work. As such, PPI for writing papers is only up 2.7%, according to BLS on FRED. while demand is expected to return and supply chains recover, paper demand will likely stay suppressed do to digital substitution. not sure if this link will work: https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/WPU0911#0

I think the situation is a bit different than 2009 crisis. There are few new elements. One is the transition to online and electronic documents / paperless offices which has accelerated lately. This will reduce paper production, which will push for a price increase due to reversed mass scale effect. Sustainability will also have a word. EU will continue to reinforce the sustainable tree cut laws even the sources are outside EU. The suppliers have to demonstrate the raw materials are managed in a sustainable way. And this is raising up prices. Higher prices will also have their effect on consumption. Prices will scale up until finding a new balance. The 2021 inflation, increasing transportation costs and raw materials prices might count for at least 2% increase in price index between May this year and the same month next year. Even the inflation, transportation and raw materials costs increase will stagnate, it is less probably the trend will reverse. St. Louis Fed has online utility charting overall PPI for Pulp, Paper, Wood products (Index 1982 = 100) and this reveals that following the sharp contraction in PPI for wood products at the time of the Financial Crisis in 2009 (when demand was similarly impacted), PPI rebounded 38% in the following year, almost symmetrical with the decline. Focusing more closely on Writing and Printing Paper, the change was much less dramatic, but still exhibited some of the peak-to-trough-to-recovery symmetry. PPI for Writing and Printing paper declined 4.5% from Dec '19 to April '20 and has since rebounded 3.2%. leaving room for additional recovery. As compared to the the aftermath of the Financial Crisis, there is even greater risk of inflation from a variety of factors in the current environment, suggesting PPI will exceed pre-pandemic levels.
